The saddle saga: bats in Borneo
Our columnists learn how to shoot a blowpipe in Indonesian Borneo as they travel from London to Sydney by bicycle.
Image 1 of 3	One man had found some bats hiding in some bamboo - they were destined for the pot Image 1 of 3	A longboat on the River Lemanak Image 1 of 3	We hit the target but I doubt we'll be hunting for our food any time soon 11:56AM BST 25 Oct 2012
Comments
“Hello Mister,” shouted a young man from his zooming moped - just one of the hoards of vehicles rampaging through the streets of Pontianak, Indonesian Borneo. We’d become trapped in the oil town after failing to secure flights to other parts of the island and were making do with Togu, the equatorial monument, and $10 cups of civet coffee that are not as bad as the method of harvest would suggest. I’d been standing at the side of the dusty street for 10 minutes waiting to cross. Doing so here is a balancing act between your patience and suicidal tendencies. I was more patient than I thought. Eventually a man on a moped stopped. Julio offered to take me to Togu on the back of his scooter. Instead of taking me there, however, we went back to his family home for tea and pictures. We met more locals when a group of school children found us and asked if we’d help with their English homework. Of course we were happy to and spent a morning playing the roles of customers to their waiters and receptionists. They bought us t-shirts as a thank you. On one occasion I nipped out of the scorching sun into a mall to enjoy its air conditioning. As I wondered around I began to feel eyes upon me. I turned to see a group of kids, 30 or more, following me. I felt like the Pied Piper. When a few began to ask me for money I quickly exited, back into the heat and hustle. Related Articles
