The busy streets of Pontianak were at odds with an Iban tribal longhouse we visited on our way to Brunei. The trip was arranged with Borneo Adventures’ guide, Juay. He was an exceptional guide and knowledgeable, not only about the Iban tribe, but the other tribes of Borneo; the Bidayuh and Orangulu. Our longhouse, deep in the forest, was built next to the Lemanak River and only reachable via a boat ride through it‘s shallow waters. Stairs lead up to a dimly lit communal area that stretched almost the length of a football field. Here we were welcomed with a shot of sweet rice wine called tuak. Leading off to the left were family rooms and to the right a raised platform, where we'd be sleeping that exited out to gardens of cocoa, pepper and rice. The Ngemahili Longhouse had 32 families living under the corrugated iron roof. Although the experience is meant for tourists, our hosts's way of life is no act. During the day the woman sat weaving baskets, chatting and watching over the children, while the men gathered food in the surrounding forest, harvested their crops or fished in the tranquil waters of the river. After a tuak-fuelled evening we accompanied Juay into the jungle in the cool of the morning where we found the male members of the tribe searching for food. One man had found some bats hiding in some bamboo - they were destined for the pot. We were taught how to shoot a blowpipe. We did hit the target but I doubt we’ll be hunting for our food any time soon. We’ll stick to the peanut butter sandwiches. Leaving the longhouse we made our way into the kingdom of Brunei and its small capital of Bandar Seri Begawan. There we met and were taken to dinner by Faten. She worked for the Brunei tourist agency and had some suggestions for us. Unfortunately, diving and golf were out of bounds with our budget. Our time in Borneo over, we headed back to Kuala Lumpur, where possible fame and fortune awaited us in the form of TV, radio and newspaper interviews about our trip so far. As it stands, we expect to reach Sydney in less than two months now. Matt McDonald and Andy Madeley are cycling from London to Sydney to raise money for War Child. Follow their route at www.thecyclediaries.com
